# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: transfer-rna
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] Klug was born in Želva, in Lithuania, to Jewish parents Lazar, a cattleman, and Bella (née Silin) Klug, with whom he emigrated to South Africa at the age of two.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] Paul de Kruif's 1926 book, *Microbe Hunters*, aroused his interest in microbiology.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] Klug was part of the Hashomer Hatzair Jewish Zionist youth movement in South Africa.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He started to study microbiology, but then moved into physics and maths, graduating with a Bachelor of Science degree at the University of the Witwatersrand, in Johannesburg.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] James and obtained his Master of Science degree at the University of Cape Town.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He was awarded an 1851 Research Fellowship from the Royal Commission for the Exhibition of 1851, which enabled him to move to England, completing his PhD in research physics at Trinity College, Cambridge in 1953.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] Following his PhD, Klug moved to Birkbeck College in the University of London in late 1953, and started working with chemist and X-ray crystallographer Rosalind Franklin in the lab of crystallographer John Bernal.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] This experience aroused a lifelong interest in the study of viruses, and during his time there he made discoveries in the structure of the tobacco mosaic virus.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] In 1962 he moved to the newly built Medical Research Council (MRC) Laboratory of Molecular Biology (LMB) in Cambridge.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He studied the structure of transfer RNA, and found what is known as zinc fingers as well as the neurofibrils in Alzheimer's disease.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] Also in 1962, Klug became a Fellow of Peterhouse, Cambridge.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He was later made an Honorary Fellow of the college.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] Between 1986 and 1996, Klug was director of the LMB.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He served on the Advisory Council for the Campaign for Science and Engineering.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He also served on the Board of Scientific Governors at The Scripps Research Institute.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He and Dai Rees approached the Wellcome Trust to found the Wellcome Sanger Institute, which was a key player in the Human Genome Project.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] Klug was awarded the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize from Columbia University in 1981.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He was knighted by Elizabeth II in 1988.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] In 1969 he was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS), the oldest national scientific institution in the world.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He was elected its President (PRS) from 1995 to 2000.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He was appointed to the Order of Merit in 1995 – as is customary for Presidents of the Royal Society.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] In 2000, Klug received the Golden Plate Award of the American Academy of Achievement.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] In 2005, he was awarded South Africa's Order of Mapungubwe (gold) for exceptional achievements in medical science.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He was elected a Fellow of the Academy of Medical Sciences (FMedSci), also in 2005.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] In 2013, Israel's Ben-Gurion University of the Negev dedicated their centre for structural biology in Klug's name, *Aaron Klug Integrated Centre for Biomolecular Structure*.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He, his family and the then-British Ambassador to Israel Matthew Gould, were in attendance.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] Klug was associated with the university and the town of Be'er Sheva, having visited them numerous times.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] Klug married Liebe Bobrow in 1948; they had two sons, one of whom predeceased them in 2000.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] He died on 20 November 2018 in Cambridge.
[src:transfer-rna/aaron-klug] Though Klug had faced discrimination in South Africa, he remained religious and according to Sydney Brenner, he became more religious in his older age.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:transfer-rna/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Aconitase has two slightly different structures, depending on whether it is activated or inactivated.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] In the inactive form, its structure is divided into four domains.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Counting from the N-terminus, only the first three of these domains are involved in close interactions with the [3Fe-4S] cluster, but the active site consists of residues from all four domains, including the larger C-terminal domain.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] The Fe-S cluster and a SO2− 4 anion also reside in the active site.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] When the enzyme is activated, it gains an additional iron atom, creating a [4Fe-4S] cluster.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] However, the structure of the rest of the enzyme is nearly unchanged; the conserved atoms between the two forms are in essentially the same positions, up to a difference of 0.1 angstroms.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] In contrast with the majority of iron–sulfur proteins that function as electron carriers, the iron–sulfur cluster of aconitase reacts directly with an enzyme substrate.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Aconitase has an active [Fe4S4]2+ cluster, which may convert to an inactive [Fe3S4]+ form.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Three cysteine (Cys) residues have been shown to be ligands of the [Fe4S4] centre.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] In the active state, the labile iron ion of the [Fe4S4] cluster is not coordinated by Cys but by water molecules.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] The iron-responsive element-binding protein (IRE-BP) and 3-isopropylmalate dehydratase (α-isopropylmalate isomerase; EC 4.2.1.33), an enzyme catalysing the second step in the biosynthesis of leucine, are known aconitase homologues.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Iron regulatory elements (IREs) constitute a family of 28-nucleotide, non-coding, stem-loop structures that regulate iron storage, heme synthesis and iron uptake.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] They also participate in ribosome binding and control the mRNA turnover (degradation).
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] The specific regulatory protein, the IRE-BP, binds to IREs in both 5' and 3' regions, but only to RNA in its apo form (without the Fe–S cluster).
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Expression of IRE-BP in cultured cells has revealed that the protein functions either as an active aconitase, when cells are iron-replete, or as an active RNA-binding protein, when cells are iron-depleted.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Mutant IRE-BPs, in which any or all of the three Cys residues involved in Fe–S formation are replaced by serine, have no aconitase activity, but retain RNA-binding properties.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Aconitase is inhibited by fluoroacetate, therefore fluoroacetate is poisonous.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Fluoroacetate, in the citric acid cycle, is converted to fluorocitrate by citrate synthase.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Fluorocitrate competitively inhibits aconitase halting the citric acid cycle.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] The iron–sulfur cluster is highly sensitive to oxidation by superoxide.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Aconitase employs a dehydration-hydration mechanism.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] The catalytic residues involved are His-101 and Ser-642.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] His-101 protonates the hydroxyl group on C3 of citrate, allowing it to leave as water, and Ser-642 concurrently abstracts the proton on C2, creating a double bond between C2 and C3, and forming the so-called *cis*-aconitate intermediate (the two carboxyl groups on the double bond are *cis*).
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] The carbon atom from which the hydrogen is removed is the one that came from oxaloacetate in the previous step of the citric acid cycle, not the one that came from acetyl CoA, even though these two carbons are equivalent except that one is "*pro*-R" and the other "*pro*-S" (see Prochirality).
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] At this point, the intermediate is rotated 180°.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] How exactly this flip occurs is debatable.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] One theory is that, in the rate-limiting step of the mechanism, the *cis*-aconitate is released from the enzyme, then reattached in the isocitrate mode to complete the reaction.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] This rate-limiting step ensures that the right stereochemistry, specifically (2R,3S), is formed in the final product.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Another hypothesis is that *cis*-aconitate stays bound to the enzyme while it flips from the citrate to the isocitrate mode.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] In either case, flipping *cis*-aconitate allows the dehydration and hydration steps to occur on opposite faces of the intermediate.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Aconitase catalyzes *trans* elimination/addition of water, and the flip guarantees that the correct stereochemistry is formed in the product.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] Aconitases are expressed in bacteria to humans.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] In citrus fruits, a reduction of the activity of the mitochondrial aconitases likely leads to the buildup of citric acid, which is then stored in vacuoles.
[src:transfer-rna/aconitase] As the fruit matures, citric acid is returned back to the cytosol where an increase in cytosolic aconitase activity reduces its levels in the fruit.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The **adaptor hypothesis** is a theoretical scheme in molecular biology to explain how information encoded in the nucleic acid sequences of messenger RNA (mRNA) is used to specify the amino acids that make up proteins during the process of translation.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] It was formulated by Francis Crick in 1955 in an informal publication of the RNA Tie Club, and later elaborated in 1957 along with the central dogma of molecular biology and the sequence hypothesis.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] It was formally published as an article "On protein synthesis" in 1958.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The name "adaptor hypothesis" was given by Sydney Brenner.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick postulated that there must exist a small molecule to precisely recognise and bind the mRNA sequences while amino acids are being synthesised.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The hypothetical adaptor molecule was later established to be a hitherto unknown nucleic acid, transfer RNA (tRNA).
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] In 1953, English biophysicist Francis Crick and American biologist James Watson, working together at the Cavendish Laboratory of the University of Cambridge, worked out the correct description of the structure of DNA, one of the major genetic materials.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] In their follow-up paper the same year, they introduced the concept of genetic information alongside the notion that DNA and protein cloud be related.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] By 1954, it was becoming to be understood that DNA, RNA (only messenger RNA was understood at the time, but only as a vague nucleic acid, and identified as such only in 1960) and proteins were related as components of the same genetic information pathway.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] However, the structure of RNA and details of how these biological molecules related and interact with each other were still a mystery, especially on how proteins could be synthesised from nucleic acids.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Watson called this problem "the mysteries of life" in his letter to Crick.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Evidences had been accumulating since the 1940s that protein synthesis occurs simultaneously with increased level of RNA in the cytoplasm.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The relationship between DNA and RNA for protein synthesis was first hypothesised by French biologist André Boivin and Roger Vendrely in 1947.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] They wrote in *Experientia* (later renamed *Cellular and Molecular Life Sciences*): "Through catalytic actions the macromolecular desoxyribonucleic acids govern the building of macromolecular ribonucleic acids, and, in turn, these control the production of cytoplasmic enzymes.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] In truth, the enzymic equipment results simultaneously from the effect of ribonucleic acids (catalytic action) and from the effect of substrates (mass action).
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Alexander Dounce, of the University of Rochester Medical Center in New York, came close to the correct interpretation of protein synthesis from RNA.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] In 1952, he proposed the first notion, naming it the "nucleic acid template hypotheses," that proteins were made from RNA, rather than from DNA.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Soviet-American physicist George Gamow was the first to come up with a coherent scheme for protein synthesis from DNA.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Based on the Watson-Crick model, he envisaged that the DNA itself is a direct template for protein synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Assuming that the four bases of DNA could produce 20 different combinations as triplets, he suggested that the different amino acids must correspond to a twenty-letter alphabet of the nucleotide sequence.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] In such configuration, the DNA directly produces proteins from the free molecules of amino acids.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Watson, then at the California Institute of Technology in Massachusetts, also thought up the issue.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Unlike Gamow, he realised the possible importance of RNA as an intermediate stage in protein synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] He initially imagined that DNA was first converted by chemical reaction to RNA, but then changed his view to DNA as a template for RNA synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] This latter model, which he called "not ugly" was starting to become more convincing.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] To solve the riddle of protein synthesis, Gamow (as the Synthesiser) created an informal team of scientists which he called the RNA Tide Club in 1954.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] As his prediction to denote 20 amino acids, the club could have only 20 members, with the designated officers: Crick (as the Pessimist), Rich (the Lord Privy Seal) and Watson (the Optimist) among them.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Coming across Gamow's paper, Crick immediately noticed some issues in the scheme.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The first was that he and Watson never had before counted the 20 amino acids or the possible 20 nucleotide triplets (although Gamow was subsequently proven to be correct and his model was the first prediction of the genetic code).
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The other issue was that RNA and protein synthesis appeared to exclusively take place in the cytoplasm, and not in the nucleus, indicating that DNA to protein pathway requires just not direct chemical binding, but some kind of mediator must be involved.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick began to think of a solution to this problem in the line of Watson's idea that the role of RNA was overlooked.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] He rejected Gamow's assumption that molecules like amino acids that are too different chemically from nucleic acid that it would be structurally impossible to bind to DNA.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Instead, he visualised a certain kind but unknown molecule that linked nucleic acids and carry amino acids to ribosomes to form peptide chains.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] As he discussed it with his colleague Sydney Brenner about the features of such molecule, Brenner was impressed with the idea and named the concept as the "adaptor hypothesis".
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The adaptor was then a hypothetical molecule that apparently help in an indirect interaction between DNA, RNA and amino acids during protein synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick admitted that he had no way knowing what kind of chemical substance was an adaptor, but then prudently suggested that it was composed of nucleotides, a sort of RNA, that had common features of both DNA and RNA.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] He even speculated that "insulin, for example, are probably RNA-made proteins.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Perhaps a special class of DNA-made proteins exists, almost always in small quantities (and thus normally overlooked).
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The adaptor hypothesis was fully formalised in 1957.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick presented the elaborate explanation in a lecture titled "Protein synthesis" on 19 September 1957 at the Society for Experimental Biology symposium on the Biological Replication of Macromolecules, held at University College London.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The adaptor hypothesis was framed to explain how information could be extracted from a nucleic acid and used to put together a string of amino acids in a specific sequence, that sequence being determined by the nucleotide sequence of the nucleic acid (DNA or RNA) template.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick proposed that each amino acid is first attached to its own specific "adaptor" piece of nucleic acid (in an enzyme-catalysed reaction).
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The order of assembly of the amino acids is then determined by a specific recognition between the adaptor and the nucleic acid which is serving as the informational template.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] In this way the amino acids could be lined up by the template in a specific order.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Coupling between adjacent amino acids would then lead to the synthesis of a polypeptide whose sequence is determined by the template nucleic acid.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick's thinking behind this proposal was based on a general consideration of the chemical properties of the two classes of molecule — nucleic acids and proteins.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] The amino acids are characterised by having a variety of side chains which vary from being hydrophilic to hydrophobic: their individual characters reside in the very different properties these side chains have.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] By contrast, a nucleic acid is composed of a string of nucleotides whose sequence presents a geometrically defined surface for hydrogen bonding.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] This makes nucleic acids good at recognising each other, but poor at distinguishing the varied side chains of amino acids.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Although his concept about the direct synthesis of amino acid from the DNA double strands was proven false, his prediction on the nature of amino acids and how they were coded by the DNA sequences (triplet nucleotides) were confirmed the key components of protein synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] This broad concept is now known as the genetic code.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] As Crick was lecturing on his hypothesis, such adaptors do exist in nature was already discovered by the team of Mahlon Hoagland and Paul Zamecnik, whose paper was published the following year in March 1958.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] These "soluble RNAs" are now called transfer RNAs and mediate the translation of messenger RNAs on ribosomes according to the rules contained in the genetic code.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] Crick imagined that his adaptors would be small, perhaps 5-10 nucleotides long.
[src:transfer-rna/adaptor-hypothesis] In fact, they are much larger, having a more complex role to play in protein synthesis, and are closer to 100 nucleotides in length.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Adenine has a central role in cellular respiration.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] It is part of adenosine triphosphate which provides the energy that drives and supports most activities in living cells, such as protein synthesis, muscle contraction, and nerve impulse propagation.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] In respiration it also participates as part of the cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide, flavin adenine dinucleotide, and coenzyme A.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] It is also part of adenosine, adenosine monophosphate, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, adenosine diphosphate, and S-adenosylmethionine.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Adenine forms several tautomers, compounds that can be rapidly interconverted and are often considered equivalent.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] However, in isolated conditions, i.e. in an inert gas matrix and in the gas phase, mainly the 9H-adenine tautomer is found.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Purine metabolism involves the formation of adenine and guanine.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Both adenine and guanine are derived from the nucleotide inosine monophosphate (IMP), which in turn is synthesized from a pre-existing ribose phosphate through a complex pathway using atoms from the amino acids glycine, glutamine, and aspartic acid, as well as the coenzyme tetrahydrofolate.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Patented August 20, 1968, the current recognized method of industrial-scale production of adenine involves heating formamide under 120 °C.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Adenine is one of the two purine nucleobases (the other being guanine) used in forming nucleotides of the nucleic acids.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] In DNA, adenine binds to thymine via two hydrogen bonds to assist in stabilizing the nucleic acid structures.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] In RNA, which is used for protein synthesis, adenine binds to uracil.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Adenine forms adenosine, a nucleoside, when attached to ribose, and deoxyadenosine when attached to deoxyribose.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] It forms adenosine triphosphate (ATP), a nucleoside triphosphate, when three phosphate groups are added to adenosine.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Adenosine triphosphate is used in cellular metabolism as one of the basic methods of transferring chemical energy between chemical reactions.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] ATP is thus a derivative of adenine, adenosine, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, and adenosine diphosphate.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] In older literature, adenine was sometimes called **Vitamin B4**, but is no longer considered a vitamin.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Due to it being synthesized by the body and not essential to be obtained by diet, it does not meet the definition of vitamin and is no longer part of the Vitamin B complex.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] However, two B vitamins, niacin and riboflavin, bind with adenine to form the essential cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) and flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), respectively.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Hermann Emil Fischer was one of the early scientists to study adenine.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] It was named in 1885 by Albrecht Kossel after Greek *ἀδήν* aden "gland", in reference to the pancreas, from which Kossel's sample had been extracted.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] Adenine can be prepared from ammonia and hydrogen cyanide (HCN) in aqueous solution, a process that has implications for the origin of life on Earth.
[src:transfer-rna/adenine] On August 8, 2011, a report, based on NASA studies with meteorites found on Earth, was published suggesting building blocks of DNA and RNA (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) may have been formed extraterrestrially in outer space.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Most White people have both major isozymes, while approximately 36% of East Asians have the cytosolic isozyme but not a functional mitochondrial isozyme.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] A remarkably higher frequency of acute alcohol intoxication among East Asians than among Whites could be related to this absence of a catalytically active form of ALDH2.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The increased exposure to acetaldehyde in individuals with the catalytically inactive form may also confer greater susceptibility to many types of cancer.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The *ALDH2* gene is about 44 kbp in length and contains at least 13 exons which encode 517 amino acid residues.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Except for the signal NH2-terminal peptide, which is absent in the mature enzyme, the amino acid sequence deduced from the exons coincided with the reported primary structure of human liver ALDH2.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Several introns contain Alu repetitive sequences.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] A TATA-like sequence (TTATAAAA) and a CAAT-like sequence (GTCATCAT) are located 473 and 515 bp, respectively, upstream from the translation initiation codon.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] ALDH2 is a tetrameric enzyme that contains three domains; two dinucleotide-binding domains and a three-stranded beta-sheet domain.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The active site of ALDH2 is divided into two halves by the nicotinamide ring of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+).
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Adjacent to the A-side (Pro-R) of the nicotinamide ring is a cluster of three cysteines (Cys301, Cys302 and Cys303) and adjacent to the B-side (Pro-S) are Thr244, Glu268, Glu476 and an ordered water molecule bound to Thr244 and Glu476.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Although there is a recognizable Rossmann fold, the coenzyme-binding region of ALDH2 binds NAD+ in a manner not seen in other NAD+-binding enzymes.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The positions of the residues near the nicotinamide ring of NAD+ suggest a chemical mechanism whereby Glu268 functions as a general base through a bound water molecule.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The sidechain amide nitrogen of Asn169 and the peptide nitrogen of Cys302 are in position to stabilize the oxyanion present in the tetrahedral transition state prior to hydride transfer.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The functional importance of residue Glu487 now appears to be due to indirect interactions of this residue with the substrate-binding site via Arg264 and Arg475.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Mitochondrial aldehyde dehydrogenase belongs to the aldehyde dehydrogenase family of enzymes that catalyze the chemical transformation from acetaldehyde to acetic acid.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Aldehyde dehydrogenase is the second enzyme of the major oxidative pathway of alcohol metabolism.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Human ALDH2 is especially efficient on acetaldehyde compared to ALDH1.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Additionally, ALDH2 functions as a protector against oxidative stress.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The inactivating ALDH2*2 mutation is "the most common single point mutation in humans".
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] This mutation is found in very few White people, but about 50% of East Asians are heterozygous for this mutation.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The ALDH2*2 allele encodes lysine instead of glutamic acid at amino acid 487, distorting the NAD+ binding site.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] ALDH2 assembles and functions as a tetramer and requires all four of its components to be active in order to metabolize acetaldehyde.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] People heterozygous for ALDH2*2 have only 10% to 45% enzyme activity, while those homozygous for ALDH2*2 have as little as 1% to 5% remaining activity.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The lack of ALDH2 activity has a number of consequences, detailed in section § Inhibition and genetic deficiency below.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] In the overall Japanese population, about 57% of individuals are homozygous for the normal allele, 40% are heterozygous for the ALDH2*2 allele, and 3% are homozygous for the ALDH2*2 allele.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The best-known consequence of ALDH2 dysfunction is in relation to the consumption of ethanol.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] People heterozygous or homozygous for the ALDH2*2 metabolize ethanol to acetaldehyde normally but metabolize acetaldehyde poorly.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] As a result, they accumulate increased levels of acetaldehyde after consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Effects include facial flushing (i.e. the "alcohol flush reaction"), urticaria, systemic dermatitis, and alcohol-induced respiratory reactions such as rhinitis and the exacerbation of asthma bronchoconstriction.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] People with a genetic ALDH2*2 deficiency have historically had a lower likelihood of developing alcoholism, both from stronger adverse effects and a possible reduction of dopamine release.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] However, this effect is not absolute: during the 1980s, there has been a steady increase in the number of Japanese alcoholics who carry the ALDH2*2 mutation.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] A strong social pressure to drink have overcome this genetic barrier to alcoholism.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] Disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2 and causes a similar effect, has been used as an alcohol-quitting aid.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] More recently, ALDH2 has been implicated in a number of pathways beyond alcohol metabolism.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] ALDH2 dysfunction is supposedly associated with a variety of human diseases including diabetes, neurodegenerative diseases, cardiovascular diseases and stroke, cancer, Fanconi anemia, pain, osteoporosis, and the process of aging.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] A case-control study in a Japanese population showed that deficiency of ALDH2 activity influences the risk for late-onset Alzheimer's disease.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] The ALDH2 knockout mice display age-related memory deficits in various tasks, as well as endothelial dysfunction, brain atrophy, and other Alzheimer's disease-associated pathologies, including marked increases in lipid peroxidation products, amyloid-beta, p-tau and activated caspases.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] These behavioral and biochemical Alzheimer's disease-like deficits were efficiently ameliorated when these mice were treated with isotope-reinforced lipids (deuterated polyunsaturated fatty acids).
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] An activator of ALDH2 enzymatic activity, Alda-1 (N-(1,3-benzodioxol-5-ylmethyl)-2,6-dichlorobenzamide), has been shown to reduce ischemia-induced cardiac damage caused by myocardial infarction.
[src:transfer-rna/aldh2] ALDH2 has been shown to interact with GroEL.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:transfer-rna/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The process of translation starts with the information stored in the nucleotide sequence of DNA.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] This is first transformed into mRNA, then tRNA specifies which three-nucleotide codon from the genetic code corresponds to which amino acid.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Each mRNA codon is recognized by a particular type of tRNA, which docks to it along a three-nucleotide anticodon, and together they form three complementary base pairs.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] On the other end of the tRNA is a covalent attachment to the amino acid corresponding to the anticodon sequence, with each type of tRNA attaching to a specific amino acid.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Because the genetic code contains multiple codons that specify the same amino acid, there are several tRNA molecules bearing different anticodons which carry the same amino acid.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The covalent attachment to the tRNA 3' end is catalysed by enzymes called aminoacyl tRNA synthetases.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] During protein synthesis, tRNAs with attached amino acids are delivered to the ribosome by proteins called elongation factors, which aid in association of the tRNA with the ribosome, synthesis of the new polypeptide, and translocation (movement) of the ribosome along the mRNA.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] If the tRNA's anticodon matches the mRNA, another tRNA already bound to the ribosome transfers the growing polypeptide chain from its 3' end to the amino acid attached to the 3' end of the newly delivered tRNA, a reaction catalyzed by the ribosome.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] A large number of the individual nucleotides in a tRNA molecule may be chemically modified, often by methylation or deamidation.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] These unusual bases sometimes affect the tRNA's interaction with ribosomes and sometimes occur in the anticodon to alter base-pairing properties.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] This reverse polymerization mechanism is biochemically unique and evolutionarily conserved, highlighting its fundamental importance in tRNA maturation.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Homologs of Thg1 are found in all domains of life, where they can also participate in tRNA repair and quality control.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The presence of G-1 is a key identity element for tRNA-His, and its absence severely impairs histidylation efficiency and tRNA function.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The structure of tRNA can be decomposed into its primary structure, its secondary structure (usually visualized as the *cloverleaf structure*), and its tertiary structure (all tRNAs have a similar L-shaped 3D structure that allows them to fit into the P and A sites of the ribosome).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The cloverleaf structure becomes the 3D L-shaped structure through coaxial stacking of the helices, which is a common RNA tertiary structure motif.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The lengths of each arm, as well as the loop 'diameter', in a tRNA molecule vary from species to species.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] An **anticodon** is a unit of three nucleotides corresponding to the three bases of an mRNA codon.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Each tRNA has a distinct anticodon triplet sequence that can form 3 complementary base pairs to one or more codons for an amino acid.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Some anticodons pair with more than one codon due to wobble base pairing.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Frequently, the first nucleotide of the anticodon is one not found on mRNA: inosine, which can hydrogen bond to more than one base in the corresponding codon position.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] In genetic code, it is common for a single amino acid to be specified by all four third-position possibilities, or at least by both pyrimidines and purines; for example, the amino acid glycine is coded for by the codon sequences GGU, GGC, GGA, and GGG.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Other modified nucleotides may also appear at the first anticodon position—sometimes known as the "wobble position"—resulting in subtle changes to the genetic code, as for example in mitochondria.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The possibility of wobble bases reduces the number of tRNA types required: instead of 61 types with one for each sense codon of the standard genetic code), only 31 tRNAs are required to translate, unambiguously, all 61 sense codons.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] A tRNA is commonly named by its intended amino acid (e.g. tRNA-Asn), by its anticodon sequence (e.g. tRNA(GUU)), or by both (e.g. tRNA-Asn(GUU) or tRNAAsn GUU).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Aminoacylation is the process of adding an aminoacyl group to a compound.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] It covalently links an amino acid to the CCA 3′ end of a tRNA molecule.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Each tRNA is aminoacylated (or *charged*) with a specific amino acid by an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] There is normally a single aminoacyl tRNA synthetase for each amino acid, despite the fact that there can be more than one tRNA, and more than one anticodon for an amino acid.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Recognition of the appropriate tRNA by the synthetases is not mediated solely by the anticodon, and the acceptor stem often plays a prominent role.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Certain organisms can have one or more aminophosphate-tRNA synthetases missing.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] This leads to charging of the tRNA by a chemically related amino acid, and by use of an enzyme or enzymes, the tRNA is modified to be correctly charged.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] For example, *Helicobacter pylori* has glutaminyl tRNA synthetase missing.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Thus, glutamate tRNA synthetase charges tRNA-glutamine(tRNA-Gln) with glutamate.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] An amidotransferase then converts the acid side chain of the glutamate to the amide, forming the correctly charged gln-tRNA-Gln.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The ribosome has three binding sites for tRNA molecules that span the space between the two ribosomal subunits: the A (aminoacyl), P (peptidyl), and E (exit) sites.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] In addition, the ribosome has two other sites for tRNA binding that are used during mRNA decoding or during the initiation of protein synthesis.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] These are the T site (named elongation factor Tu) and I site (initiation).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] By convention, the tRNA binding sites are denoted with the site on the small ribosomal subunit listed first and the site on the large ribosomal subunit listed second.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] For example, the A site is often written A/A, the P site, P/P, and the E site, E/E.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The binding proteins like L27, L2, L14, L15, L16 at the A- and P- sites have been determined by affinity labeling by A.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Once translation initiation is complete, the first aminoacyl tRNA is located in the P/P site, ready for the elongation cycle described below.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] During translation elongation, tRNA first binds to the ribosome as part of a complex with elongation factor Tu (EF-Tu) or its eukaryotic (eEF-1) or archaeal counterpart.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] This initial tRNA binding site is called the A/T site.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] In the A/T site, the A-site half resides in the small ribosomal subunit where the mRNA decoding site is located.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The mRNA decoding site is where the mRNA codon is read out during translation.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The T-site half resides mainly on the large ribosomal subunit where EF-Tu or eEF-1 interacts with the ribosome.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Once mRNA decoding is complete, the aminoacyl-tRNA is bound in the A/A site and is ready for the next peptide bond to be formed to its attached amino acid.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The peptidyl-tRNA, which transfers the growing polypeptide to the aminoacyl-tRNA bound in the A/A site, is bound in the P/P site.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Once the peptide bond is formed, the tRNA in the P/P site is acylated, or has a free 3' end, and the tRNA in the A/A site dissociates the growing polypeptide chain.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] To allow for the next elongation cycle, the tRNAs then move through hybrid A/P and P/E binding sites, before completing the cycle and residing in the P/P and E/E sites.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Once the A/A and P/P tRNAs have moved to the P/P and E/E sites, the mRNA has also moved over by one codon and the A/T site is vacant, ready for the next round of mRNA decoding.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The tRNA bound in the E/E site then leaves the ribosome.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The P/I site is actually the first to bind to aminoacyl tRNA, which is delivered by an initiation factor called IF2 in bacteria.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] However, the existence of the P/I site in eukaryotic or archaeal ribosomes has not yet been confirmed.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The P-site protein L27 has been determined by affinity labeling by E.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Organisms vary in the number of tRNA genes in their genome.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] For example, the nematode worm *C. elegans*, a commonly used model organism in genetics studies, has 29,647 genes in its nuclear genome, of which 620 code for tRNA.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The budding yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* has 275 tRNA genes in its genome.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The number of tRNA genes per genome can vary widely, with bacterial species from groups such as Fusobacteria and Tenericutes having around 30 genes per genome while complex eukaryotic genomes such as the zebrafish (*Danio rerio*) can bear more than 10 thousand tRNA genes.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] One study has shown that the copy number of tRNA genes varies among individuals.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] As with all eukaryotes, there are 22 mitochondrial tRNA genes in humans.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Mutations in some of these genes have been associated with severe diseases like the MELAS syndrome.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Regions in nuclear chromosomes, very similar in sequence to mitochondrial tRNA genes, have also been identified (tRNA-lookalikes).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] These tRNA-lookalikes are also considered part of the nuclear mitochondrial DNA (genes transferred from the mitochondria to the nucleus).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The phenomenon of multiple nuclear copies of mitochondrial tRNA (tRNA-lookalikes) has been observed in many higher organisms from human to the opossum suggesting the possibility that the lookalikes are functional.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] In humans, cytoplasmic tRNA genes can be grouped into 49 families according to their anticodon features.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] These genes are found on all chromosomes, except the 22 and Y chromosome.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] High clustering on 6p is observed (140 tRNA genes), as well as on chromosome 1.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The HGNC, in collaboration with the Genomic tRNA Database (GtRNAdb) and experts in the field, has approved unique names for human genes that encode tRNAs.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Typically, tRNA genes from Bacteria are shorter (mean = 77.6 bp) than those from Archaea (mean = 83.1 bp) and eukaryotes (mean = 84.7 bp).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The mature tRNA follows an opposite pattern, with tRNAs from Bacteria being usually longer (median = 77.6 nt) than tRNAs from Archaea (median = 76.8 nt), with eukaryotes exhibiting the shortest mature tRNAs (median = 74.5 nt).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Genomic tRNA content is a differentiating feature of genomes among biological domains of life: Archaea present the simplest situation in terms of genomic tRNA content with a uniform number of gene copies, Bacteria have an intermediate situation and Eukarya present the most complex situation.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Eukarya present not only more tRNA gene content than the other two kingdoms but also a high variation in gene copy number among different isoacceptors, and this complexity seem to be due to duplications of tRNA genes and changes in anticodon specificity.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Evolution of the tRNA gene copy number across different species has been linked to the appearance of specific tRNA modification enzymes (uridine methyltransferases in Bacteria, and adenosine deaminases in Eukarya), which increase the decoding capacity of a given tRNA.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] As an example, tRNAAla encodes four different tRNA isoacceptors (AGC, UGC, GGC and CGC).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] In Eukarya, AGC isoacceptors are extremely enriched in gene copy number in comparison to the rest of isoacceptors, and this has been correlated with its A-to-I modification of its wobble base.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] This same trend has been shown for most amino acids of eukaryal species.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Indeed, the effect of these two tRNA modifications is also seen in codon usage bias.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Highly expressed genes seem to be enriched in codons that are exclusively using codons that will be decoded by these modified tRNAs, which suggests a possible role of these codons—and consequently of these tRNA modifications—in translation efficiency.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Many species have lost specific tRNAs during evolution.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] For instance, both mammals and birds lack the same 14 out of the possible 64 tRNA genes, but other life forms contain these tRNAs.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] For translating codons for which an exactly pairing tRNA is missing, organisms resort to a strategy called wobbling, in which imperfectly matched tRNA/mRNA pairs still give rise to translation, although this strategy also increases the propensity for translation errors.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The reasons why tRNA genes have been lost during evolution remains under debate but may relate improving resistance to viral infection.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Because nucleotide triplets can present more combinations than there are amino acids and associated tRNAs, there is redundancy in the genetic code, and several different 3-nucleotide codons can express the same amino acid.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] This codon bias is what necessitates codon optimization.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The top half of tRNA (consisting of the T arm and the acceptor stem with 5′-terminal phosphate group and 3′-terminal CCA group) and the bottom half (consisting of the D arm and the anticodon arm) are independent units in structure as well as in function.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The top half may have evolved first including the 3′-terminal genomic tag which originally may have marked tRNA-like molecules for replication in early RNA world.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The bottom half may have evolved later as an expansion, e.g. as protein synthesis started in RNA world and turned it into a ribonucleoprotein world (RNP world).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] This proposed scenario is called genomic tag hypothesis.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] In fact, tRNA and tRNA-like aggregates have an important catalytic influence (i.e., as ribozymes) on replication still today.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] These roles may be regarded as 'molecular (or chemical) fossils' of RNA world.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] In March 2021, researchers reported evidence suggesting that an early form of transfer RNA could have been a replicator ribozyme molecule in the very early development of life, or abiogenesis.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Evolution of type I and type II tRNAs is explained to the last nucleotide by the three 31 nucleotide minihelix tRNA evolution theorem, which also describes the pre-life to life transition on Earth.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Three 31 nucleotide minihelices of known sequence were ligated in pre-life to generate a 93 nucleotide tRNA precursor.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] To generate type II tRNAs, a single internal 9 nucleotide deletion occurred within ligated acceptor stems (CCGCCGCGCGGCGG goes to GGCGG).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] To generate type I tRNAs, an additional, related 9 nucleotide deletion occurred within ligated acceptor stems within the variable loop region (CCGCCGCGCGGCGG goes to CCGCC).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] These two 9 nucleotide deletions are identical on complementary RNA strands. tRNAomes (all of the tRNAs of an organism) were generated by duplication and mutation.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Very clearly, life evolved from a polymer world that included RNA repeats and RNA inverted repeats (stem-loop-stems).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Of particular importance were the 7 nucleotide U-turn loops (CU/???AA).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] After LUCA (the last universal common (cellular) ancestor), the T loop evolved to interact with the D loop at the tRNA "elbow" (T loop: UU/CAAAU, after LUCA).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Polymer world progressed to minihelix world to tRNA world, which has endured for ~4 billion years.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Analysis of tRNA sequences reveals a major successful pathway in evolution of life on Earth.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] tRNA-derived fragments (or tRFs) are short molecules that emerge after cleavage of the mature tRNAs or the precursor transcript.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Both cytoplasmic and mitochondrial tRNAs can produce fragments.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] There are at least four structural types of tRFs believed to originate from mature tRNAs, including the relatively long tRNA halves and short 5'-tRFs, 3'-tRFs and i-tRFs.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The precursor tRNA can be cleaved to produce molecules from the 5' leader or 3' trail sequences.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Cleavage enzymes include Angiogenin, Dicer, RNase Z and RNase P.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Half-tRNAs cleaved by angiogenin are also known as tiRNAs.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The biogenesis of smaller fragments, including those that function as piRNAs, are less understood.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] tRFs have multiple dependencies and roles; such as exhibiting significant changes between sexes, among races and disease status.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Functionally, they can be loaded on Ago and act through RNAi pathways, participate in the formation of stress granules, displace mRNAs from RNA-binding proteins or inhibit translation.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] At the system or the organismal level, the four types of tRFs have a diverse spectrum of activities.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Functionally, tRFs are associated with viral infection, cancer, cell proliferation and also with epigenetic transgenerational regulation of metabolism.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] tRFs are not restricted to humans and have been shown to exist in multiple organisms.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Two online tools are available for those wishing to learn more about tRFs: the framework for the interactive exploration of mitochondrial and nuclear tRNA fragments (MINTbase) and the relational database of Transfer RNA related Fragments (tRFdb Archived 2024-03-15 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] MINTbase also provides a naming scheme for the naming of tRFs called tRF-license plates (or MINTcodes) that is genome independent; the scheme compresses an RNA sequence into a shorter string.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] tRNAs with modified anticodons and/or acceptor stems can be used to modify the genetic code.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Scientists have successfully repurposed codons (sense and stop) to accept amino acids (natural and novel), for both initiation (see: start codon) and elongation.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] In 1990, tRNAfMet2 CUA (modified from the tRNAfMet2 CAU gene metY) was inserted into *E. coli*, causing it to initiate protein synthesis at the UAG stop codon, as long as it is preceded by a strong Shine-Dalgarno sequence.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] At initiation it not only inserts the traditional formylmethionine, but also formylglutamine, as glutamyl-tRNA synthase also recognizes the new tRNA.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The experiment was repeated in 1993, now with an elongator tRNA modified to be recognized by the methionyl-tRNA formyltransferase.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] A similar result was obtained in *Mycobacterium*.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Later experiments showed that the new tRNA was orthogonal to the regular AUG start codon showing no detectable off-target translation initiation events in a genomically recoded *E. coli* strain.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] In eukaryotic cells, tRNAs are transcribed by RNA polymerase III as pre-tRNAs in the nucleus.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] RNA polymerase III recognizes two highly conserved downstream promoter sequences: the 5′ intragenic control region (5′-ICR, D-control region, or A box), and the 3′-ICR (T-control region or B box) inside tRNA genes.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The first promoter begins at +8 of mature tRNAs and the second promoter is located 30–60 nucleotides downstream of the first promoter.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The transcription terminates after a stretch of four or more thymidines.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Pre-tRNAs undergo extensive modifications inside the nucleus.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Some pre-tRNAs contain introns that are spliced, or cut, to form the functional tRNA molecule; in bacteria these self-splice, whereas in eukaryotes and archaea they are removed by tRNA-splicing endonucleases.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Eukaryotic pre-tRNA contains bulge-helix-bulge (BHB) structure motif that is important for recognition and precise splicing of tRNA intron by endonucleases.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] This motif position and structure are evolutionarily conserved.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] However, some organisms, such as unicellular algae have a non-canonical position of BHB-motif as well as 5′- and 3′-ends of the spliced intron sequence.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The 5′ sequence is removed by RNase P, whereas the 3′ end is removed by the tRNase Z enzyme.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] A notable exception is in the archaeon *Nanoarchaeum equitans,* which does not possess an RNase P enzyme and has a promoter placed such that transcription starts at the 5′ end of the mature tRNA.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The non-templated 3′ CCA tail is added by a nucleotidyl transferase.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Before tRNAs are exported into the cytoplasm by Los1/Xpo-t, tRNAs are aminoacylated.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The order of the processing events is not conserved.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] For example, in yeast, the splicing is not carried out in the nucleus but at the cytoplasmic side of mitochondrial membranes.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The existence of tRNA was first hypothesized by Francis Crick as the "adaptor hypothesis" based on the assumption that there must exist an adapter molecule capable of mediating the translation of the RNA alphabet into the protein alphabet.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Paul C Zamecnik, Mahlon Hoagland, and Mary Louise Stephenson discovered tRNA in 1958.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Significant research on structure was conducted in the early 1960s by Alex Rich and Donald Caspar, two researchers in Boston, the Jacques Fresco group in Princeton University and a United Kingdom group at King's College London.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Holley of Cornell University reported the primary structure and suggested three secondary structures. tRNA was first crystallized in Madison, Wisconsin, by Robert M.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The cloverleaf structure was ascertained by several other studies in the following years and was finally confirmed using X-ray crystallography studies in 1974.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Two independent groups, Kim Sung-Hou working under Alexander Rich and a British group headed by Aaron Klug, published the same crystallography findings within a year.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Interference with aminoacylation may be useful as an approach to treating some diseases: cancerous cells may be relatively vulnerable to disturbed aminoacylation compared to healthy cells.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] The protein synthesis associated with cancer and viral biology is often very dependent on specific tRNA molecules.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] For instance, for liver cancer charging tRNA-Lys-CUU with lysine sustains liver cancer cell growth and metastasis, whereas healthy cells have a much lower dependence on this tRNA to support cellular physiology.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Similarly, hepatitis E virus requires a tRNA landscape that substantially differs from that associated with uninfected cells.
[src:transfer-rna/transfer-rna] Hence, inhibition of aminoacylation of specific tRNA species is considered a promising novel avenue for the rational treatment of a plethora of diseases.
